AB  - Chinese hog production has undergone a significant structural change, shifting from small-scale to intensive systems. Few studies have quantitatively analyzed the relationship between intensification and pollutant nutrient emissions in Chinese hog production. In this study, we first propose an analytical framework from which we determine the effect of intensification on pollutant nutrient emissions, and deduce the theoretical hypothesis. Then, based on a microeconomic survey data set of 754 hog farms from five provinces in China, we provide a careful empirical analysis to verify the proposed hypothesis using ordinary least squares (OLS) and instrumental-variable two-stage least squares (IV-2SLS) regression models. The empirical results show that there is an inverted U-shaped relationship between intensification and pollutant nutrient emissions, and that medium-scale hog farms perform the worst from an environmental point of view. The degree of integration of crop and hog production, environmental regulation, and financial capacity are the main mechanisms responsible for the inverted U-shaped curve. We suggest that enhancing environmental performance in the intensification of hog production requires having fewer farms with a higher production density, because this will cause less environmental damage than having a higher number of farms with a lower production density. Our conclusions provide an important scientific basis for the sustainable intensification of livestock production in China, as well as in other countries confronting a similar situation.
