KW  - FARMERS
KW  - RESILIENCE
KW  - EXPERIENCE
AB  - Floods pose significant and far-reaching threats to rural communities, particularly in regions where livelihoods rely heavily on agriculture and natural resources. These impacts include damage to agricultural land, loss of livestock, destruction of infrastructure, population displacement, and cascading economic, social, and environmental challenges. Such disruptions often drive increased migration from rural areas, especially in developing countries-raising the risk that large portions of these communities could eventually become uninhabitable. This study aimed to investigate the factors influencing the adoption of protective measures prior to flooding among rural populations in Iran. The research focused on households in Shushtar County, located in Khuzestan Province in southwestern Iran. Data were collected through a structured questionnaire, and the results were analyzed using structural equation modeling (SEM). The theoretical framework extended the protection motivation theory (PMT) by incorporating two additional variables: flood experience (FE) and social capital (SC), alongside the core constructs of perceived vulnerability (PV), response efficacy (RE), response cost (RC), and self-efficacy (SE). The enhanced model demonstrated a 22 % improvement in predictive power compared to the original PMT, ultimately explaining 85.9 % of the variance in the adoption of protective measures prior to flood events. These findings not only bridge a critical gap in the existing literature but also offer practical guidance for policymakers seeking to strengthen rural flood preparedness. The newly developed model provides a robust framework for designing targeted interventions to mitigate flood impacts and enhance community resilience.
