TI  - Access to plant protection products: significant differences between European sugar beet growers and cane growers from other countries
T2  - SUGAR INDUSTRY INTERNATIONAL
LA  - English
KW  - sugar beet
KW  - sugarcane
KW  - plant protection products
KW  - pesticides
KW  - health
KW  - safety
KW  - environment
KW  - biodiversity
KW  - regulations
KW  - European Union
AB  - Managing crop protection has become a challenge and a key economic and political issue for European sugar beet growers. In Europe, the authorization process for plant protection products is very strict, based on the precautionary principle. It is regularly reinforced and depends on a high level of human health, biodiversity and environmental protection. This has led to a significant loss in plant protection products (PPPs) in the past few years, especially for sugar beet growers, without sufficient effective alternatives coming on-stream. The beet growers' toolbox is shrinking. Consequently, the risk of yield loss or crop failure has increased, as informed by productivity declines. The recent political choices and decisions in Europe, as well as the impacts of climate change, are accentuating this trend: European farmers are experiencing a new research phase in modernizing their crop cultivation to adapt to these challenges. However, European sugar beet growers are moving into markets connected to global sugar markets, and their competitiveness remains crucial. In other competitive sugar-producing countries the context is quite different. Analyzing the regulatory framework of PPPs in some cane sugar-producing countries shows big differences with Europe, and these differences are increasing. The analysis indicates that countries such as India, Brazil, and Australia do not have the same approach to regulation and do not apply the same level of protection of the environment, biodiversity, and health as in the EU. This raises the issue of a level playing field for European growers regarding production standards. Given the commitment of all major countries to reduce the overall risks from PPPs and highly hazardous chemicals, European beet growers call on governments and Institutions to harmonize their respective regulatory frameworks urgently and effectively. Offsetting and balancing the differences is essential. At least banning hazardous PPPs should be consensual.
